 t11 Sharing Economy: How Digital Technologies Have Changed Economic Reality -- t12 The Impact of the Fourth Industrial Revolution on the Socio-Economic Development of the World Economy -- tPart IV: High Technologies and State Management in Industry 4.0 -- t13 Economics of Industry 4.0 in the Political Economy Paradigm -- t14 Features of the Company’s Organizational Culture -- t15 Harmonizing the Interests of the State and Business in Stakeholder Management -- t16 Methodological Approaches to Tender Procedures in Corporate Procurement Management in Companies -- tConclusion: Future Perspectives of Industry 4.0 -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIndustry 4.0 is not only just a new sector of economy—it is a new technological model of economic development, which will determine the technical possibilities, organizational philosophies, and approaches to managing socio-economic systems in the near future. Signs of the Fourth Industrial Revolution can already be seen in the most progressive developed and developing countries. However, despite the high interest of entrepreneurs in the possibilities that are provided by Industry 4.0, large-scale investment projects and the adoption of state and national strategies and programs to facilitate the financing and transition to Industry 4.0, the Fourth Industrial Revolution is developing very slowly. The reason for this is the non-systemic character of the implemented initiatives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aIndustry 4.0.  aeconomy.  alaw.  amanagement.1 aAbdusalomova, Nodira B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl'pidovskaya, Marina L., eeditor.4edt